{{ill|Yamauchi Shrine|ja|山内神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamauchi Shrine|qq=}} (山内神社) is a [[Shinto shrine]] in [[Kōchi, Kōchi]]..<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roberts|first=Luke S.|date=1994|title=The Petition Box in Eighteenth-Century Tosa|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/133199|journal=Journal of Japanese Studies|volume=20|issue=2|pages=423–458|doi=10.2307/133199|issn=0095-6848}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roberts|first=Luke|date=2001-01-01|title=Translation of the Memorial of Imakita Sakubei to the Lord of Tosa, Yamauchi Toyochika|url=https://www.academia.edu/77719195/Translation_of_the_Memorial_of_Imakita_Sakubei_to_the_Lord_of_Tosa_Yamauchi_Toyochika|journal=Early Modern Japan: an interdisciplinary journal}}</ref>  It used to be a [[Beppyo Shrine]], which is a shrine with a significant history and special importance. However, it left the Beppyo list in 2013.

== History ==
In the 3rd year of [[Bunka (era)|Bunka]] ({{ill|1806|ja|1806年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1806|qq=}}), under the 10th feudal lord of the Tosa Domain, {{ill|Toyosaku Yamanouchi|ja|山内豊策|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyosaku Yamanouchi|qq=}}, the Fujinami Shrine was built within {{ill|Kōchi Castle|ja|高知城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōchi Castle|qq=}} to enshrine the first lord of the domain, {{ill|Kazutoyo Yamanouchi|ja|山内一豊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kazutoyo Yamanouchi|qq=}}, his wife {{ill|Kenshoin (Kazutoyo Yamanouchi's wife)|ja|見性院（千代）|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenshoin (Kazutoyo Yamanouchi's wife)|qq=}}, and the second lord {{ill|Tadayoshi Yamanouchi|ja|山内忠義|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tadayoshi Yamanouchi|qq=}}. At that time, it was common for each domain to enshrine their first lord as a deity. In the 6th year of [[Tenpō|Tenpō]] ({{ill|1835|ja|1835年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1835|qq=}}), the title of "Fujinami Daimyōjin" was bestowed.

In the 4th year of [[Meiji|Meiji]] ({{ill|1871|ja|1871年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1871|qq=}}), the last (16th) lord of the Tosa Domain and the first domain governor, {{ill|Toyonori Yamanouchi|ja|山内豊範|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyonori Yamanouchi|qq=}}, established the Yamanouchi Shrine at its current location, which had been the temporary shrine of the Fujinami Shrine, to enshrine the spirits of the lords from the 3rd lord {{ill|Tadayoshi Yamanouchi|ja|山内忠豊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tadayoshi Yamanouchi|qq=}} to the 14th lord {{ill|Toyomasa Yamanouchi|ja|山内豊惇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyomasa Yamanouchi|qq=}}. The following year, in the 5th year of Meiji ({{ill|1872|ja|1872年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1872|qq=}}), Yamanouchi Shrine was handed over to the Kōchi Prefecture and Ranked as a village shrine.

In the 7th year of [[Shōwa|Shōwa]] ({{ill|1933|ja|1933年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1933|qq=}}), a new shrine was constructed to honor the achievements of the 15th lord {{ill|Toyonobu Yamanouchi|ja|山内容堂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyonobu Yamanouchi|qq=}} (Toyonobu) and the 16th lord Toyonori during the Meiji Restoration. The spirits of the successive lords enshrined at the Yamanouchi Shrine were moved to the Fujinami Shrine, and a new shrine building was constructed. The new shrine was completed in April of the 10th year of Shōwa ({{ill|1935|ja|1935年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1935|qq=}}) and was established as a special government shrine, the "Bekakkōhei-sha Yamanouchi Shrine", enshrining Toyonobu and Toyonori.

In the 20th year of Shōwa ({{ill|1945|ja|1945年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1945|qq=}}), both shrines were destroyed by fire during the war, and thereafter, rituals were held in temporary shrines. In the 45th year of Shōwa ({{ill|1970|ja|1970年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1970|qq=}}), the shrine buildings were rebuilt, and the Fujinami Shrine was merged, becoming a shrine that enshrines all the successive lords of the Tosa Domain. In the 2nd year of [[Heisei|Heisei]] ({{ill|1990|ja|1990年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1990|qq=}}), the Kumano, Kasuga, and Sumiyoshi shrines, which had been within Kōchi Castle, were moved to the shrine grounds.

