== History ==
In the 3rd year of [[Bunka (era)|Bunka]] ([[:en:1806|1806]]), under the 10th feudal lord of the Tosa Domain, {{ill|Toyosaku Yamanouchi|ja|山内豊策|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyosaku Yamanouchi|qq=}}, the Fujinami Shrine was built within [[:en:Kōchi Castle|Kōchi Castle]] to enshrine the first lord of the domain, [[:en:Yamauchi Kazutoyo|Kazutoyo Yamanouchi]], his wife {{ill|Kenshoin (Kazutoyo Yamanouchi's wife)|ja|見性院（千代）|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenshoin (Kazutoyo Yamanouchi's wife)|qq=}}, and the second lord {{ill|Tadayoshi Yamanouchi|ja|山内忠義|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tadayoshi Yamanouchi|qq=}}. At that time, it was common for each domain to enshrine their first lord as a deity. In the 6th year of [[Tenpō|Tenpō]] ([[:en:1835|1835]]), the title of "Fujinami Daimyōjin" was bestowed.

In the 4th year of [[Meiji|Meiji]] ([[:en:1871|1871]]), the last (16th) lord of the Tosa Domain and the first domain governor, [[:en:Yamauchi Toyonori|Toyonori Yamanouchi]], established the Yamanouchi Shrine at its current location, which had been the temporary shrine of the Fujinami Shrine, to enshrine the spirits of the lords from the 3rd lord {{ill|Tadayoshi Yamanouchi|ja|山内忠豊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tadayoshi Yamanouchi|qq=}} to the 14th lord {{ill|Toyomasa Yamanouchi|ja|山内豊惇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyomasa Yamanouchi|qq=}}. The following year, in the 5th year of Meiji ([[:en:1872|1872]]), Yamanouchi Shrine was handed over to the Kōchi Prefecture and Ranked as a village shrine.

In the 7th year of [[Shōwa|Shōwa]] ([[:en:1933|1933]]), a new shrine was constructed to honor the achievements of the 15th lord [[:en:Yamauchi Toyoshige|Toyonobu Yamanouchi]] (Toyonobu) and the 16th lord Toyonori during the Meiji Restoration. The spirits of the successive lords enshrined at the Yamanouchi Shrine were moved to the Fujinami Shrine, and a new shrine building was constructed. The new shrine was completed in April of the 10th year of Shōwa ([[:en:1935|1935]]) and was established as a special government shrine, the "Bekakkōhei-sha Yamanouchi Shrine", enshrining Toyonobu and Toyonori.

In the 20th year of Shōwa ([[:en:1945|1945]]), both shrines were destroyed by fire during the war, and thereafter, rituals were held in temporary shrines. In the 45th year of Shōwa ([[:en:1970|1970]]), the shrine buildings were rebuilt, and the Fujinami Shrine was merged, becoming a shrine that enshrines all the successive lords of the Tosa Domain. In the 2nd year of [[Heisei|Heisei]] ([[:en:1990|1990]]), the Kumano, Kasuga, and Sumiyoshi shrines, which had been within Kōchi Castle, were moved to the shrine grounds.

